specJson.name: brightics.function.timeseries$auto_arima_train
specJson.label: Auto ARIMA Train
specJson.description:
## Description
Auto ARIMA model automatically discovers the optimal parameters for an ARIMA model, settling on a single fitted ARIMA model.

Auto ARIMA works by conducting differencing tests (i.e., Kwiatkowski–Phillips–Schmidt–Shin, Augmented Dickey-Fuller or Phillips–Perron) to determine the order of differencing, `d`, and then fitting models within ranges of defined `Max p`, `Max_q` ranges. 

ARIMA is usually used to monitor if there is abnormal value on trend by reviewing data on a weekly/monthly basis or to predict future values on a quarter/yearly basis. A strength of ARIMA compared to ARMA is it can be adapted to data which shows non-stationary series. Stationary series is a type of series which average and variance are unchangeable regardless of time transition. In case of non-stationary series, it is normally analyzed after stabilizing it with log or difference.

params.label: Input Columns
params.description: Input column names. Only values in numeric type are possible.

params.label: Max p
params.description: The maximum p to test for ARIMA(p,d,q). The p means order (number of time lags) of the autoregressive model.

params.label: Max q
params.description: The maximum q to test for ARIMA(p,d,q). The q means order of the moving-average model.

params.label: d (the degree of differencing)
params.description: The degree of differencing. If empty, this will be selected automatically.

md: # Auto ARIMA Train This function trains a time series data using a non-seasonal Auto ARIMA model. ## Description Auto ARIMA model automatically discovers the optimal parameters for an ARIMA model, settling on a single fitted ARIMA model. Auto ARIMA works by conducting differencing tests (i.e., Kwiatkowski–Phillips–Schmidt–Shin, Augmented Dickey-Fuller or Phillips–Perron) to determine the order of differencing, `d`, and then fitting models within ranges of defined `Max p`, `Max_q` ranges. ARIMA is usually used to monitor if there is abnormal value on trend by reviewing data on a weekly/monthly basis or to predict future values on a quarter/yearly basis. A strength of ARIMA compared to ARMA is it can be adapted to data which shows non-stationary series. Stationary series is a type of series which average and variance are unchangeable regardless of time transition. In case of non-stationary series, it is normally analyzed after stabilizing it with log or difference. Reference - - ## Properties ### VA #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one column for time series data. #### OUTPUT 1. **model**: (Model) Trained Auto ARIMA Time Series model. #### PARAMETER 1. **Input Columns***: Input column names. Only values in numeric type are possible. 2. **Max p**: The maximum p to test for ARIMA(p,d,q). The p means order (number of time lags) of the autoregressive model. 3. **Max q**: The maximum q to test for ARIMA(p,d,q). The q means order of the moving-average model. 4. **d (the degree of differencing)**: The degree of differencing. If empty, this will be selected automatically. 5. **Group By**: Columns to group by. ### Python #### USAGE ``` auto_arima_train(table, input_cols, max_p=5, d=None, max_q=5, group_by=None) ``` #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one column for time series data. #### OUTPUT 1. **model**: (Model) Trained Auto ARIMA Time Series model. #### PARAMETER 1. **input_cols***: Input column names. Only values in numeric type are possible. * Type: *list[str]* * Default: None 2. **max_p**: The maximum p to test for ARIMA(p,d,q). The p means order (number of time lags) of the autoregressive model. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 5 (value >= 2) 3. **max_q**: The maximum q to test for ARIMA(p,d,q). The q means order of the moving-average model. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 5 (value >= 2) 4. **d**: The degree of differencing. If empty, this will be selected automatically. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: None (0 <= value <= 2) 5. **group_by**: Columns to group by. * Type: *list[str]* ## Example ### VA **[Related Tutorial]** **[Sample Model]** In this tutorial workflow, sample_timeseries data is used to train an Auto ARIMA Time Series. The generated model is afterward applied to a test dataset to predict the _future value at certain time point_ by using Auto ARIMA Predict function. The parameter settings used in the function are shown below. ++Parameters++ 1. **Input Columns***: data2 2. **Max p**: 5 3. **Max q**: 5 4. **d (the degree of differencing)**: None 5. **Group By**: None ### Python ``` from brightics.function.timeseries import auto_arima_train input_table = inputs[0] result = auto_arima_train(table=input_table, input_cols=['data2'], max_p=5, d=None, max_q=5, group_by=None) output = result['model'] ``` In this python script, sample_timeseries data is used to train an Auto ARIMA Time Series. The generated model can be applied to a test dataset to predict the _future value at certain time point_ by using Auto ARIMA Predict function.
